WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.840
novel BCL2 inhibitor, and we'll talk about data in mantle cell lymphoma.

00:00:06.500 --> 00:00:11.520
So before we're talking about the novel BCL2 inhibitor, we're going to review data real quick

00:00:11.520 --> 00:00:16.500
for the first in-class BCL2 inhibitor of needle flax in mantle cell. The first data actually came

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:24.640
from the first inhuman paper by David. In that paper, there was a small number of mantle cell

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:31.480
patients included, which were PTK inhibitor naive. The response was 75% was 21% CL. The

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:40.160
median PF was 11. So it's really decent data. But this drug didn't move forward. There's some

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:45.680
historical challenges with some... The way the trial was done, then the partner drug was pulled

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:48.680
off the market and whatever. We're not going to talk about that today.

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:54.640
And then in real world study, there's some off-label use of

00:00:54.640 --> 00:01:01.120
needle flax. Toby Iyer published the UK experience with 20 patients. 53% response rate was 18% CR.

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:06.640
The PFS is really disappointing, only 3.2 months. Then Yazeed, you have the data here with

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:12.400
either single agent or combination in relapsed mantle cell lymphoma.

00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:18.880
Most patients with PTK inhibitor exposed. In this series, the overall response rate 40%,

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:24.320
CR 16%. The PFS was equally disappointing, only at 3.7 months.

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:31.600
So how does Sunrel compare to needle flax? It's more potent. As we heard from the talks

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:38.480
in the last couple of days, 14-fold more potent. It's also six-fold more selective versus BCL2XL.

00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:45.840
The half-life is shorter. So that potentially can make the TRS monitoring a little

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:53.680
simplified. But the dose ramp-up is a little still confident. We still need to figure that out. But

00:01:53.680 --> 00:01:58.640
at least you don't need to monitor the TRS labs at 12 or 24 hours.

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:07.440
So this is the 2-0-1 study of needle flax in relapsed mantle cell lymphoma. Patients must

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:13.280
have had a prior PTK inhibitor. So this trial had a part one with dose escalation and safety

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:21.920
expansion, and then part two for efficacy expansion at the ideal dose. So this is the patient population.

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:28.960
You can see a typical relapsed mantle cell population, elderly, male predominance.

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:36.720
87% of the patients were refractory to the last line of therapy. It really speaks to the difficult

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:47.680
to treat cohort nature. In terms of high risk features, you see a 42% patient had a high K67,

00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:50.720
35% had TBG3 mutation. Close to 60% had three or more K67 mutations. As you can see, a lot of patients

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:51.120
were refractory to the last line of therapy, really speaks to the difficult to treat cohort nature. In terms of high risk features, you see a 42% patient had a high K67, 35% had TBG3 mutation. Close to 60% had three or more K67 mutations. As we heard from the talks in the last couple of days,

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:51.120
In terms of risk features, you see a 42% patient had a high K67 mutation. Close to 60% had three or more K67 mutations. As we heard from the talks in the last couple of days,

00:02:52.720 --> 00:02:59.840
all lines of therapy previously and all of them had a PTK inhibitor and 20% had actually two or more PTK inhibitors.

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:07.040
So in terms of safety, the most common O grade treatment emergent AE

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:15.120
were hematological or something related to tumor cell apoptosis. And you can see on the right,

00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:22.400
the neutropenia, thrombocytopenia, anemia, the hematological AEs were pretty frequent.

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:28.480
And then you have electrolyte abnormalities related to some component of TLS. TLS did happen

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:35.200
in eight patients and by definition, those are all grade three or above, but only two were clinical,

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:40.320
six were in laboratory, and all of these resolved without any issues. Infections are frequent,

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:48.480
39% and 16.5% were grade three. So it's not necessarily very easy to deal with.

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:52.160
In terms of efficacy, the response rate is 52%.

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:58.240
This is only looking at a patient in the part two, the efficacy expansion part.

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:05.680
The CR rate is 15.5%. If you only look at the response rates, probably similar to needle clax

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:16.240
data. The subgroup analysis in terms of response rate, you can see this high response rate of about

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:21.920
50% across pretty much all groups. And just highlighted, even for patients

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:28.480
with TPH3 mutation, the response rate is close to 60%. The one subgroup that had maybe slightly

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:34.480
lower response rate at 41% is the folks with high MIPE scores, about one third of the patients.

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:42.960
In terms of time to event data, the figure shows your duration response, not progression-free

00:04:42.960 --> 00:04:50.480
survival. So duration response median is 16 months. Median progression-free survival is 6.5 months.

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:56.480
It's not fantastic, but numerically better than what we saw with needle clax in BTK-exposed setting.

00:04:57.280 --> 00:04:59.840
Median overall survival has not been reached.

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:06.400
So how do these efficacy data compare with other BCL2 inhibitors or other available therapies?

00:05:06.400 --> 00:05:11.840
So this is another BCL2 inhibitor that was presented to ASH this year.

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:20.240
The trial was done in China. The response rate in this small cohort appears to be very high, 84% and

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:28.880
36% CR rate. Median progression-free survival is 8 months. So it looks quite promising, but

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:33.200
we don't know a lot of the details of the patient population there, and

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:37.600
especially prior lines of therapy and all of that. So we'll see whether they have expansion.

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:41.840
I'm not sure this drug will come to the United States anyway.

00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:47.920
Peritoneal was approved. Response rate, if you guys recall, is about in the 50% range as well.

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:52.320
Median progression-free survival is 7 months. Overall survival looks pretty good.

00:05:53.680 --> 00:06:01.680
But putting all these together, so seronoclax can, mind you, the response rate 52%, 60% CR,

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:08.000
median PF is 6.5, comparing that to Pertol, very similar. So how do we choose?

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:15.120
Seronoclax may be getting an accelerated approval label real soon. So how do I choose?

00:06:15.120 --> 00:06:17.680
I would like to use both. So I'm not going to, you know,

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:21.680
keep the conversation with the sponsors. We should do a trial with the combination.

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:23.680
That's it. Thank you.
